## Framework 4: Self-Determination Theory (Deci & Ryan)

### The 3 Psychological Needs

**Autonomy** — "I'm in control"  
**Competence** — "I'm getting better"  
**Relatedness** — "I'm part of something"

### How Winzinvest Already Satisfies These

| Need | How Winzinvest Delivers | Enhancement Opportunity |
|---|---|---|
| **Autonomy** | User sets all rules, system just executes | Add "rule override history" — show when you broke your own rules |
| **Competence** | Dashboard shows regime, conviction, signals | Add skill progression: Novice → Practitioner → Expert (based on mastery) |
| **Relatedness** | Founding Member community | Add anonymized peer benchmarking (not leaderboard) |

### Autonomy-Supportive Features

From SDT research, autonomy increases when you:
- Provide **choice** (multiple strategies, opt-in features)
- Remove **pressure** (no "you should trade more" messaging)
- Give **rationale** (explain WHY the system blocked a trade)

**Implementation:**
- **"Why was this blocked?"** button on every rejected signal (educational, not punitive)
- **Opt-in everything** — notifications, emails, automation modes
- **Kill switch control** — user can halt system any time (ultimate autonomy)

### Competence-Supportive Features

Competence grows when challenges match skill level and feedback is immediate.

**Implementation:**
- **Beginner → Advanced modes**:
  - Beginner: System shows fewer signals (high conviction only), explains every decision
  - Advanced: Shows all signals, user decides which gates to relax
- **Instant feedback**: Dashboard updates within 5 seconds of any action
- **Skill challenges**: "Can you identify which regime we're in from the chart?" (quiz, not mandatory)

### Relatedness-Supportive Features

Connection to others who share your goals.

**Implementation:**
- **Founding Member directory** (opt-in, first name + location only)
- **Case study library** — "How other traders use Winzinvest" (anonymized)
- **Peer benchmarking** — "Your drawdown handling is tighter than 78% of users" (NOT leaderboard, no names)

